SIMPLE: wanton
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wanton
<hw>Wan"ton</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wantoun</ets>, contr. from <ets>wantowen</ets>; pref.
<ets>wan-</ets> wanting (see <er>Wane</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>), hence
expressing negation + <ets>towen</ets>, p. p., AS. <ets>togen</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>te⟦oacute⟧n</ets> to draw, to educate, bring up; hence,
properly, ill bred. See <er>Tug</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Untrained; undisciplined; unrestrained; hence,
loose; free; luxuriant; roving; sportive.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In woods and
<xex>wanton</xex> wilderness.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Spenser.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧A wild and
<xex>wanton</xex> herd.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>wanton</qex> and a merry [friar].</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[She] her unadorned golden tresses wore⟦br⟧
Disheveled, but in <qex>wanton</qex> ringlets waved.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How does your tongue grow <qex>wanton</qex> in her praise!</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wandering from moral rectitude; perverse;
dissolute.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Men grown <xex>wanton</xex> by
prosperity.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Roscommon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Specifically: Deviating from the rules of chastity;
lewd; lustful; lascivious; libidinous; lecherous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not with <qex>wanton</qex> looking of folly.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Thou art] froward by nature, enemy to peace,⟦br⟧
Lascivious, <qex>wanton</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Reckless; heedless; <as>as, <ex>wanton</ex>
mischief</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wanton</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wanton
<hw>Wan"ton</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A roving, frolicsome
thing; a trifler; -- used rarely as a term of endearment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am afeard you make a <qex>wanton</qex> of me.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Peace, my <qex>wantons</qex>; he will do⟦br⟧
More than you can aim unto.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One brought up without restraint; a pampered
pet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Anything, sir,⟦br⟧
That's dry and wholesome; I am no bred <qex>wanton</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A lewd person; a lascivious man or woman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wanton</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wanton
<hw>Wan"ton</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wantoned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wantoning</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To rove and ramble without restraint, rule, or
limit; to revel; to play loosely; to frolic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature here <qex>wantoned</qex> as in her prime.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How merrily we would sally into the fields, and strip under the
first warmth of the sun, and <qex>wanton</qex> like young dace in the
streams!</q> <rj><qau>Lamb.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To sport in lewdness; to play the wanton; to play
lasciviously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wanton</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wanton
<hw>Wan"ton</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to become wanton; also,
to waste in wantonness.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wantonize</ent>⟦br⟧
